04535nam a22005895i 9780300206777DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002067777 a10.12987/97803002067772doi  a(DE-B1597)485834  a(OCoLC)878109262  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aDS134.4b.B66 2014 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a940.53/180922aB2231 aBonelli, Charlotte R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aExit Berlin :bHow One Woman Saved Her Family from Nazi Germany /cCharlotte R. Bonelli. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tHecht and Isack Family Trees -- tHow It All Began -- tPART ONE: May 1933–September 1938 -- t1. Berlin Beginnings -- t2. From Hecht to Hatch: American Relations -- t3. First Requests -- t4. Persistence Rewarded -- tPART TWO: December 1938–August 1939 -- t5. Settling In: A New Life in New York -- t6. Looking Back Home -- t7. Escape to Shanghai -- t8. A Widening Circle -- tPART THREE: September 1939–October 1941 -- t9. Desperate Appeals -- t10. The Shanghai Solution -- t11. Rosh Hashana, 1940 -- t12. Deportation to Gurs: ILOT K -- t13. A Closing Door -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJust a week after the Kristallnacht terror in 1938, young Luzie Hatch, a German Jew, fled Berlin to resettle in New York. Her rescuer was an American-born cousin and industrialist, Arnold Hatch. Arnold spoke no German, so Luzie quickly became translator, intermediary, and advocate for family left behind. Soon an unending stream of desperate requests from German relatives made their way to Arnold’s desk.   Luzie Hatch had faithfully preserved her letters both to and from far-flung relatives during the World War II era as well as copies of letters written on their behalf. This extraordinary collection, now housed at the American Jewish Committee Archives, serves as the framework for Exit Berlin. Charlotte R. Bonelli offers a vantage point rich with historical context, from biographical information about the correspondents to background on U.S. immigration laws, conditions at the Vichy internment camps, refuge in Shanghai, and many other topics, thus transforming the letters into a riveting narrative.   Arnold’s letters reveal an unfamiliar side of Holocaust history. His are the responses of an “average” American Jew, struggling to keep his own business afloat while also assisting dozens of relatives trapped abroad—most of whom he had never met and whose deathly situation he could not fully comprehend. This book contributes importantly to historical understanding while also uncovering the dramatic story of one besieged family confronting unimaginable evil.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)vPersonal narratives. 0aJewszGermanyvCorrespondence. 0aJewszUnited StatesvCorrespondence. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewszGermany. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aBodemann, Natascha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030019752540uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030020677740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300206777423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300206777/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY